@Shankha: here's how I typically try to reproduce bugs across a range of JDT versions (running the batch compiler from a command line):
- I have a directory with versions of ecj.jar for (almost) all releases and recent milestones: $ ls ~/jdt/ecj ecj-3.2.2.jar ecj-3.3.2.jar ecj-3.4.2.jar ecj-3.5.2.jar ecj-3.6.1.jar ecj-3.6.2.jar ecj-3.6.jar ecj-3.7.1.jar ecj-3.7.2.jar ecj-3.7.jar ecj-3.8.1.jar ecj-3.8.jar ecj-4.2.2.jar ecj-4.2.jar ecj-4.3.1.jar ecj-4.3.2.jar ecj-4.3.jar ecj-4.4.1.jar ecj-4.4.jar ecj-4.5M1.jar ecj-4.5M2.jar ecj-4.5M3.jar ecj-4.5M4.jar ecj-P20140317-1600.jar
- I store the example file in a temporary directory, e.g., /tmp/bug456395/Test.java.
- I successively compile the test program with different versions of ecj, like: $ /java/jdk1.8.0/bin/java -jar ~/jdt/ecj/ecj-4.4.1.jar -1.8 Test.java $ /java/jdk1.8.0/bin/java -jar ~/jdt/ecj/ecj-4.5M1.jar -1.8 Test.java
Using a 1.8 java executable is needed when compiling at 1.8 so we find the appropriate rt.jar.
With this technique I can quickly observe that:
- the error from comment 0 is not reported from ecj >= 4.5 M2
- ecj < 4.5 M2 indeed shows:
Type mismatch: cannot convert from Map<Object,Set<Object>> to Map<String,Set<String>>
- additionally several versions report a spurious error against the method references, which, however seems to be fixed in M4 (and also M2 doesn't report those).
When reporters can provide the exact version used, this certainly helps to ensure we're chasing the same bug (the reported "Version: 4.5" in this bug is slightly misleading here). But the above approach can save us a lot of time in reproducing problems :)
Remains to be done: identify the bug that was resolved in the M2 time frame, the fix of which reproducibly toggles this bug -> mark as duplicate.
For fine-grained search of the fixing (or breaking) commit I have a slightly different compiler invocation:
$ java -classpath ~/git/eclipse.jdt.core/org.eclipse.jdt.core/bin org.eclipse.jdt.internal.compiler.batch.Main -1.8 Test.java
This takes the classfiles directly from my checked out workspace. Now I can use Eclipse to checkout (and compile) different commits (between M1 and M2 in this case), and immediately invoke the batch compiler using that particular commit. With a smart search (manually simulate 'git bisect') a few commands of this style will identify the exact commit that toggles the bug. (Unless from the list of bugs fixed in that time frame you can directly guess the duplicate and jump directly to that commit).

@Jeff: no need to mark a compiler error as "critical": we are aware that *every* bug reported against the compiler is critical for someone :) Marking "your" bug as "critical" will not rank it at higher priority than other compiler bugs, just saying ...
